<file path="agentic/prompts/generate-cf-library.md">
  1: # Prompt: Generate Client-First Library from Figma Variables
  2: 
  3: ## Purpose
  4: 
  5: This prompt template guides the LLM to auto-generate or update
  6: `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json` and
  7: `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/figma-token-map.json`
  8: from raw Figma variable data extracted via Figma MCP `get_variable_defs`.
  9: 
 10: Run `python scripts/update_library_from_figma.py --site-id <id>` first
 11: to get the step-by-step instruction block before using this template.
 12: 
 13: ---
 14: 
 15: ## Input
 16: 
 17: - Figma variables output from: `get_variable_defs(figma_file_id="<id>")`
 18: - Current library (if exists): `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json`
 19: - Current token map (if exists): `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/figma-token-map.json`
 20: 
 21: ---
 22: 
 23: ## Naming Rules
 24: 
 25: ### CF Category from Figma variable type / path
 26: 
 27: | Figma variable path contains | CF category |
 28: |---|---|
 29: | `color` / `colours` / `brand` / `palette` | → generates THREE classes: `text-color-*`, `background-color-*`, `border-color-*` |
 30: | `spacing` / `gap` / `padding` / `margin` | `spacing` |
 31: | `font-size` / `text-size` / `size/text` | `font-size` |
 32: | `font-weight` / `weight` | `font-weight` |
 33: | `radius` / `border-radius` | `border-radius` |
 34: | `opacity` / `alpha` | `opacity` |
 35: 
 36: ### Semantic name derivation
 37: 
 38: 1. Take the **last path segment** of the Figma variable path.
 39: 2. Lowercase and slugify (replace spaces with `-`, strip special chars).
 40: 3. Examples:
 41:    - `colors/brand/Primary` → `primary`
 42:    - `spacing/Large` → `large`
 43:    - `font-size/Body Default` → `body-default`
 44: 
 45: ### Full class name = `{cf_category}-{semantic_name}`
 46: 
 47: Examples:
 48: - `colors/brand/Primary` → `text-color-primary`, `background-color-primary`, `border-color-primary`
 49: - `spacing/Large` → `spacing-large`
 50: - `font-size/Body Default` → `font-size-body-default`
 51: 
 52: ### Unit conversion
 53: 
 54: - Spacing/font-size in px → divide by 16 → rem string
 55:   - `48px` → `"3rem"`
 56:   - `14px` → `"0.875rem"`
 57: - Colors: keep as hex, e.g. `"#FF5733"`
 58: - Font-weight: keep as number string, e.g. `"700"`
 59: - Border-radius in px → rem (same ÷16 rule)
 60: - Opacity: keep as decimal string, e.g. `"0.5"`
 61: 
 62: ---
 63: 
 64: ## Output Format
 65: 
 66: ### figma-token-map.json
 67: 
 68: ```json
 69: {
 70:   "figma_file_id": "<id>",
 71:   "updated_at": "<ISO8601>",
 72:   "naming_convention": {
 73:     "pattern": "{cf_category}-{semantic_name}",
 74:     "categories": ["text-color","background-color","border-color","spacing","font-size","font-weight","border-radius","opacity"]
 75:   },
 76:   "mappings": {
 77:     "colors/brand/Primary": {
 78:       "figma_value": "#FF5733",
 79:       "cf_text_class": "text-color-primary",
 80:       "cf_bg_class": "background-color-primary",
 81:       "cf_border_class": "border-color-primary"
 82:     },
 83:     "spacing/Large": {
 84:       "figma_value": "48px",
 85:       "cf_class": "spacing-large",
 86:       "rem_value": "3rem"
 87:     }
 88:   }
 89: }
 90: ```
 91: 
 92: ### client-first-library.json
 93: 
 94: ```json
 95: {
 96:   "project_id": "<site_id>",
 97:   "webflow_site_id": "<site_id>",
 98:   "figma_file_id": "<figma_file_id>",
 99:   "version": "1.0.0",
100:   "updated_at": "<ISO8601>",
101:   "classes": {
102:     "text-color-primary": {
103:       "figma_token": "colors/brand/Primary",
104:       "cf_category": "text-color",
105:       "webflow_property": "color",
106:       "value": "#FF5733",
107:       "description": "Primary brand text color"
108:     },
109:     "background-color-primary": {
110:       "figma_token": "colors/brand/Primary",
111:       "cf_category": "background-color",
112:       "webflow_property": "background-color",
113:       "value": "#FF5733",
114:       "description": "Primary brand background color"
115:     },
116:     "border-color-primary": {
117:       "figma_token": "colors/brand/Primary",
118:       "cf_category": "border-color",
119:       "webflow_property": "border-color",
120:       "value": "#FF5733",
121:       "description": "Primary brand border color"
122:     },
123:     "spacing-large": {
124:       "figma_token": "spacing/Large",
125:       "cf_category": "spacing",
126:       "webflow_property": "padding",
127:       "value": "3rem",
128:       "description": "Large spacing token"
129:     }
130:   }
131: }
132: ```
133: 
134: ---
135: 
136: ## Update Rules (when library already exists)
137: 
138: 1. **If class exists** → UPDATE `value` only. Preserve `description`, `figma_token`, `cf_category`, `webflow_property`.
139: 2. **If class is new** → ADD with full schema (all required fields).
140: 3. **If Figma token removed** → DO NOT delete class automatically. Flag it in changelog with `source: "figma_removed"` and ask PM.
141: 4. **Always** write a changelog entry for every changed or added class.
142: 
143: ---
144: 
145: ## Changelog Entry Format
146: 
147: ```json
148: {
149:   "timestamp": "<ISO8601>",
150:   "class": "text-color-primary",
151:   "old_value": null,
152:   "new_value": "#FF5733",
153:   "source": "figma_sync",
154:   "reason": "Initial generation from Figma variables"
155: }
156: ```
157: 
158: `source` values: `figma_sync` | `manual_edit` | `figma_removed`
159: 
160: ---
161: 
162: ## Validation After Writing
163: 
164: Run mandatory gate before any Webflow sync:
165: 
166: ```cmd
167: python scripts/gates/validate_project_library.py --site-id <site_id>
168: ```
169: 
170: Gate must return exit 0 before proceeding to sync.
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/read-figma-data.md">
  1: # Prompt: Read and Analyze Figma Raw Data
  2: 
  3: ## Purpose
  4: 
  5: Produce a structured **design analysis document** BEFORE writing the HTML contract.
  6: This analysis is the mandatory input to `write-html-contract.md`. Do not skip this step.
  7: 
  8: Run AFTER:
  9: 1. Figma raw data is in `workspace/rawdata/`.
 10: 2. `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md` is read.
 11: 3. Per-project CF library loaded: `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json`.
 12: 
 13: Output file: `workspace/blueprints/[page-slug]_design-analysis.json`
 14: 
 15: ---
 16: 
 17: ## Why This Step Exists
 18: 
 19: Jumping from raw Figma JSON directly to HTML contract is error-prone on complex pages.
 20: This pre-analysis step forces systematic extraction of all decisions before naming begins:
 21: - Section inventory locks the vertical order and structural sizing choices.
 22: - Layout map decides every custom class name before the contract is written.
 23: - Typography catalog maps every text style to CF utilities once, consistently.
 24: - Color catalog verifies every color token is in the library before HTML is written.
 25: 
 26: ---
 27: 
 28: ## Output: Design Analysis JSON Structure
 29: 
 30: Write `workspace/blueprints/[page-slug]_design-analysis.json` with this shape:
 31: 
 32: ```json
 33: {
 34:   "page_slug": "home",
 35:   "figma_file_id": "...",
 36:   "generated_at": "ISO date",
 37:   "section_inventory": [...],
 38:   "layout_pattern_map": [...],
 39:   "typography_catalog": [...],
 40:   "color_token_catalog": [...],
 41:   "component_map": [...],
 42:   "responsive_notes": []
 43: }
 44: ```
 45: 
 46: ---
 47: 
 48: ## Section 1: section_inventory
 49: 
 50: For each top-level section frame (in vertical order on page):
 51: 
 52: ```json
 53: {
 54:   "section_id": "hero",
 55:   "figma_node_id": "123:456",
 56:   "figma_name": "Hero Section",
 57:   "order": 1,
 58:   "container_size": "large",
 59:   "padding_section_size": "large",
 60:   "background_token": "background-color-dark",
 61:   "has_dark_bg": true,
 62:   "notes": ""
 63: }
 64: ```
 65: 
 66: Rules:
 67: - `section_id`: slugify Figma frame name (lowercase, spaces→hyphens, drop special chars)
 68: - `container_size`: apply Section C thresholds from `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md`
 69: - `padding_section_size`: apply Section D thresholds
 70: - `background_token`: CF library class name, or `null` if no background token
 71: 
 72: ---
 73: 
 74: ## Section 2: layout_pattern_map
 75: 
 76: For each flex/grid layout frame inside sections:
 77: 
 78: ```json
 79: {
 80:   "section_id": "hero",
 81:   "layouts": [
 82:     {
 83:       "figma_node_id": "123:789",
 84:       "figma_name": "Content Row",
 85:       "direction": "horizontal",
 86:       "columns": null,
 87:       "gap_px": 48,
 88:       "gap_token": "gap-medium",
 89:       "cf_decision": "utility",
 90:       "suggested_utility_classes": ["flex-horizontal", "gap-medium"],
 91:       "suggested_custom_class": null,
 92:       "case": null
 93:     }
 94:   ]
 95: }
 96: ```
 97: 
 98: Rules:
 99: - `direction`: `"horizontal"` (flex row) | `"vertical"` (flex col) | `"grid"` | `"absolute"` (no auto-layout)
100: - `columns`: number if grid, `null` if flex
101: - `gap_token`: snap to nearest Layout token name (tiny/xxsmall/xsmall/small/medium/large/xlarge/xxlarge/huge/xhuge/xxhuge or semantic gaps small/regular/medium/large)
102: - `cf_decision`: `"utility"` when flex-horizontal/flex-vertical/gap-*/grid-N-col covers it; `"custom"` only when utilities can't express it
103: - `suggested_utility_classes`: if `cf_decision=utility`, list the classes; if custom, leave empty array
104: - `suggested_custom_class`: if `cf_decision=custom`, suggest the class name using Section G naming; if utility, leave `null`
105: - `case`: only set to `"Case 1"` if `cf_decision=custom`; `null` if utility
106: 
107: ---
108: 
109: ## Section 3: typography_catalog
110: 
111: One entry per distinct text style used on the page (not per-node):
112: 
113: ```json
114: {
115:   "style_id": "figma-style-id",
116:   "figma_style_name": "Heading/H1",
117:   "font_size_px": 64,
118:   "font_size_rem": "4rem",
119:   "font_weight": 700,
120:   "cf_heading_class": "heading-style-h1",
121:   "cf_size_class": null,
122:   "cf_weight_class": null,
123:   "cf_style_classes": [],
124:   "suggested_tag": "h1",
125:   "notes": "Sole H1 on page — no heading-style class needed, tag alone"
126: }
127: ```
128: 
129: Rules:
130: - Apply Section E algorithm from `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md`
131: - `cf_heading_class`: set if semantic/visual mismatch; `null` if tag alone is correct
132: - `cf_size_class`: set for body text sizes; `null` for headings
133: - `cf_weight_class`: set if weight utility needed; `null` if weight already in heading-style or is default
134: - `cf_style_classes`: array of any `text-style-*` utilities (allcaps, italic, etc.)
135: - `font_size_rem`: `font_size_px / 16`, keep as string with rem unit; exception: 14px = "0.875rem"
136: 
137: ---
138: 
139: ## Section 4: color_token_catalog
140: 
141: One entry per Figma color variable used on the page:
142: 
143: ```json
144: {
145:   "figma_variable": "colors/brand/Primary",
146:   "library_token": "primary",
147:   "text_class": "text-color-primary",
148:   "bg_class": "background-color-primary",
149:   "border_class": "border-color-primary",
150:   "usage_contexts": ["hero heading", "CTA button fill"]
151: }
152: ```
153: 
154: Rules:
155: - Apply Section F from `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md`
156: - Look up `figma_token` in `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json`
157: - If ANY variable is NOT in the library → write a `blocker` entry and STOP. Do not proceed to HTML contract until PM resolves.
158: - If a Figma color is a hardcoded hex with no variable mapping → flag as blocker; operator must add to library first before writing HTML contract.
159: - Never hardcode hex values anywhere in the analysis or contract.
160: - **Dark Mode note:** Dark Mode is a variable collection mode (Theme collection, `mode-61994c14-2f10-542b-e084-a014a8caf47a`). Classes remain identical — the Theme variable resolves differently in Dark Mode. Document `dark_mode_value` per token for reference but do not create separate classes for dark mode. The same `text-color-primary` class works in both modes.
161: 
162: ---
163: 
164: ## Section 5: component_map
165: 
166: One entry per Figma component type used (not per-instance):
167: 
168: ```json
169: {
170:   "figma_component": "Button/Primary",
171:   "cf_pattern": "button",
172:   "variant_class": null,
173:   "instances_count": 3
174: },
175: {
176:   "figma_component": "Button/Secondary",
177:   "cf_pattern": "button",
178:   "variant_class": "is-secondary",
179:   "instances_count": 1
180: }
181: ```
182: 
183: ---
184: 
185: ## Section 6: responsive_notes
186: 
187: Flag elements that need breakpoint treatment:
188: 
189: ```json
190: {
191:   "element_class": "hero_content-row",
192:   "desktop": "flex row, 2 columns",
193:   "tablet": "flex column, 1 column",
194:   "mobile": "flex column, full width",
195:   "hide_at": null,
196:   "requires_breakpoint_custom_class": true,
197:   "case": "Case 4",
198:   "notes": "2-col → 1-col at tablet; width 100% on mobile"
199: }
200: ```
201: 
202: Rules:
203: - `requires_breakpoint_custom_class`: **Default `false` for spacing/type** — variable modes handle responsive shifts automatically. Set `true` only for structural reflow (column count, hide/show, complex positional changes that utilities can't express).
204: - `hide_at`: `"tablet"` | `"mobile-landscape"` | `"mobile-portrait"` | `null` → maps to `hide-*` utility
205: - If element is hidden at a breakpoint, use `hide-*` utility (NOT a custom class)
206: - For column reflow (e.g., 3-col desktop → 1-col mobile), use `grid-N-col-tab` / `grid-N-col-mobile` utilities — NOT a custom class; set `requires_breakpoint_custom_class: false`
207: 
208: ---
209: 
210: ## Validation Checklist Before Proceeding to HTML Contract
211: 
212: Run through this checklist after producing the analysis JSON. Do NOT proceed to `write-html-contract.md` until all pass:
213: 
214: - [ ] Every `section_id` is unique (no duplicate slugs)
215: - [ ] Section order in `section_inventory` matches Figma vertical order (top to bottom)
216: - [ ] Every color variable used on the page has a matching `library_token` in `color_token_catalog` — if any are missing, STOP and request library update from PM
217: - [ ] Every layout frame has a `suggested_class` in `layout_pattern_map` (no layout without a class name)
218: - [ ] `typography_catalog` covers every distinct text style visible on the page
219: - [ ] `component_map` covers every Figma component type used
220: - [ ] No hex values appear anywhere in the analysis JSON
221: 
222: ---
223: 
224: ## Source References
225: 
226: - `agentic/specs/figma-to-client-first-mapping.md` — Sections A–G (node types, layout, sizing, typography, colors, naming)
227: - `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json` — project token classes
228: - `knowledge-base/client-first-class-map.json` — global CF utility catalog
229: - `workspace/design-system.json` — project-specific REM scale
</file>

<file path="agentic/prompts/write-html-contract.md">
  1: # Prompt: Write HTML Contract from Figma Blueprint
  2: 
  3: ## Purpose
  4: 
  5: Guide LLM to produce the `html_contract` per section and the `new_classes` list in
  6: `workspace/blueprints/*.json`. The HTML contract is the **naming authority** — all Client-First
  7: class names are decided HERE, once, serially. Subagents in Phase 2B never invent new names.
  8: 
  9: Run AFTER:
 10: 1. Figma data is in `workspace/rawdata/` and `workspace/contents/`.
 11: 2. Per-project CF library loaded: `knowledge-base/libraries/{site_id}/client-first-library.json`.
 12: 3. Global CF class map read: `knowledge-base/client-first-class-map.json`.
 13: 
 14: ---
 15: 
 16: ## The Core Question You Must Answer for Every Element
 17: 
 18: > "Does a Client-First class already exist that does exactly this job?"
 19: 
 20: If YES → **use it, never recreate it.**
 21: If NO → **name a new custom class using `component_element` underscore convention** and add it to `new_classes`.
 22: 
 23: Getting this wrong is the #1 mistake. Over-creating classes creates bloat. Under-creating (forcing utilities to do component work) creates fragile, unmaintainable builds.
 24: 
 25: ---
 26: 
 27: ## Layer 1: Always Use These — Never Create Replacements
 28: 
 29: These six structural classes are **mandatory** on every page. They are predefined CF globals. Never invent alternatives.
 30: 
 31: | HTML tag | CF class | CSS job | Never replace with |
 32: |---|---|---|---|
 33: | `<div>` | `page-wrapper` | outermost page container | anything else |
 34: | `<main>` | `main-wrapper` | wraps all content (not nav/footer) | `<div class="main">` |
 35: | `<section>` | `section_[section-id]` | section band with anchor ID | `<div class="hero">` |
 36: | `<div>` | `padding-global` | left/right horizontal gutters only | custom padding divs |
 37: | `<div>` | `container-large` / `container-medium` / `container-small` | max-width centering | hardcoded width classes |
 38: | `<div>` | `padding-section-small` / `padding-section-medium` / `padding-section-large` | top/bottom vertical rhythm | custom top/bottom padding |
 39: 
 40: **Rule:** `padding-global` wraps `container-*`. `container-*` wraps content. Nesting order is fixed.
 41: 
 42: ```html
 43: <!-- CORRECT structural skeleton -->
 44: <div class="page-wrapper">
 45:   <main class="main-wrapper">
 46:     <section class="section_hero">
 47:       <div class="padding-global">
 48:         <div class="container-large">
 49:           <div class="padding-section-large">
 50:             <!-- content here -->
 51:           </div>
 52:         </div>
 53:       </div>
 54:     </section>
 55:   </main>
 56: </div>
 57: ```
 58: 
 59: **Section styling note:** Do not put visual styles (background color, text color) directly on `section_[name]`. For section-level visual variants, use a combo add-on class on the same section element:
 60: 
 61: ```html
 62: <!-- CORRECT: structural class + style variant combo -->
 63: <section class="section_pricing section-style-dark">
 64: 
 65: <!-- WRONG: visual styles on structural class -->
 66: <section class="section_pricing">  <!-- with background-color set on section_pricing itself -->
 67: ```
 68: 
 69: `section-style-dark`, `section-style-brand` — these global style combos let you toggle section appearance without overriding the structural class.
 70: 
 71: ---
 72: 
 73: ## Layer 2: Existing Utility Classes — Check Before Creating
 74: 
 75: These cover **single-purpose, globally reusable CSS properties**. If a Figma property maps cleanly to one of these, use it. No underscore = utility class = no custom equivalent needed.
 76: 
 77: ### Typography utilities (text deviating from default HTML tag style)
 78: 
 79: | Property needed | Use this class |
 80: |---|---|
 81: | Visual h1 on a non-h1 element | `heading-style-h1` |
 82: | Visual h2 | `heading-style-h2` |
 83: | Visual h3 | `heading-style-h3` |
 84: | Visual h4 | `heading-style-h4` |
 85: | Visual h5 | `heading-style-h5` |
 86: | Visual h6 | `heading-style-h6` |
 87: | Large body text | `text-size-large` |
 88: | Medium body text | `text-size-medium` |
 89: | Regular / body text (default) | `text-size-regular` |
 90: | Small text | `text-size-small` |
 91: | Tiny / caption text | `text-size-tiny` |
 92: | All caps | `text-style-allcaps` |
 93: | Italic | `text-style-italic` |
 94: | Muted / subdued | `text-style-muted` |
 95: | Strikethrough | `text-style-strikethrough` |
 96: | No-wrap | `text-style-nowrap` |
 97: | 1-line truncation | `text-style-1line` |
 98: | 2-line truncation | `text-style-2lines` |
 99: | 3-line truncation | `text-style-3lines` |
100: | Balanced line breaks | `text-style-balance` |
101: | Orphan-free wrapping | `text-style-pretty` |
102: | Bold | `text-weight-bold` |
103: | Semibold | `text-weight-semibold` |
104: | Medium weight | `text-weight-medium` |
105: | Extra bold | `text-weight-xbold` |
106: | Normal weight | `text-weight-normal` |
107: | Light weight | `text-weight-light` |
108: | Left align | `text-align-left` |
109: | Center align | `text-align-center` |
110: | Right align | `text-align-right` |
111: | Link-styled text | `text-style-link` |
112: | Pull quote / blockquote | `text-style-quote` |
113: 
114: **Note:** `text-size-huge` does NOT exist in CF V2.2. The size scale is: tiny / small / regular / medium / large.
115: 
116: ### Color utilities (from per-project library)
117: 
118: Colors in the per-project library (`client-first-library.json`) already have three classes each:
119: 
120: | Figma color token | Apply this class for | Class name |
121: |---|---|---|
122: | any color token | text color | `text-color-[token-name]` |
123: | any color token | background | `background-color-[token-name]` |
124: | any color token | border | `border-color-[token-name]` |
125: 
126: **Example:** Figma token `colors/brand/Primary` → classes `text-color-primary`, `background-color-primary`, `border-color-primary`. All three are already in the library.
127: 
128: ### Display / visibility utilities
129: 
130: | Need | Use this class |
131: |---|---|
132: | Hide on all screens | `hide` |
133: | Hide on tablet | `hide-tablet` |
134: | Hide on mobile landscape | `hide-mobile-landscape` |
135: | Hide on mobile portrait | `hide-mobile-portrait` |
136: | Inline flex behavior | `display-inlineflex` |
137: 
138: ### Inherit utilities (override stacked color/size/weight)
139: 
140: | Need | Use this class |
141: |---|---|
142: | Text color inherits from parent | `inherit-text-color` |
143: | Font weight inherits | `inherit-text-weight` |
144: | Font size inherits | `inherit-text-size` |
145: | Text decoration inherits | `inherit-text-decoration` |
146: | Border radius inherits | `inherit-border-radius` |
147: 
148: ### Button base (always a starting base)
149: 
150: | Need | Use this class |
151: |---|---|
152: | Primary button | `button` |
153: | Secondary button variant | `button is-secondary` |
154: | Text link button variant | `button is-text` |
155: 
156: **CF V2.2 only ships `is-secondary` and `is-text` as button combos.** Do not use `is-brand` or `is-outline` — these are not CF V2.2 defaults. Any additional variant must be declared in `new_classes` with Case 5.
157: 
158: ### Max-width utilities (constrain readable line length)
159: 
160: | Need | Use this class |
161: |---|---|
162: | Constrain content width inside container | `max-width-[xxlarge\|xlarge\|large\|medium\|small\|xsmall\|xxsmall]` |
163: | Full width at tablet | `max-width-full-tablet` |
164: | Full width at mobile landscape | `max-width-full-mobile-landscape` |
165: | Full width at mobile portrait | `max-width-full-mobile-portrait` |
166: 
167: ### Icon sizing
168: 
169: | Need | Use this class |
170: |---|---|
171: | Icon with height only (variable width) | `icon-height-[small\|medium\|large]` |
172: | Square icon (equal w+h) | `icon-1x1-[small\|medium\|large]` |
173: 
174: ### Advanced layout / decoration utilities
175: 
176: | Need | Use this class |
177: |---|---|
178: | Hide overflow (image crop, mask) | `overflow-hidden` |
179: | Scrollable container | `overflow-scroll` / `overflow-auto` |
180: | Square 1:1 aspect ratio | `aspect-ratio-square` |
181: | Portrait 2:3 aspect ratio | `aspect-ratio-portrait` |
182: | Landscape 3:2 aspect ratio | `aspect-ratio-landscape` |
183: | Widescreen 16:9 aspect ratio | `aspect-ratio-widescreen` |
184: | Full-cover absolute layer | `layer` |
185: 
186: **Note: all `aspect-ratio-*` classes include `object-fit:cover` — no separate object-fit class needed for images. Real ratios: portrait=2/3, landscape=3/2 (not 3/4 or 4/3).**
187: | Inline flex (badge/tag chip) | `display-inlineflex` |
188: | z-index 1 | `z-index-1` |
189: | z-index 2 | `z-index-2` |
190: | Disable pointer events | `pointer-events-none` |
191: | Restore pointer events | `pointer-events-auto` |
192: | Reset all margin and padding | `spacing-clean` |
193: 
194: ### Spacer (dedicated vertical gap element)
195: 
196: | Need | Use this class |
197: |---|---|
198: | Vertical space between siblings | `spacer-[tiny\|small\|medium\|large\|huge]` |
199: 
200: Use a plain `<div class="spacer-medium">` as a dedicated spacer div. Do NOT apply margin directly on content elements for sibling spacing — use a spacer div or spacing wrapper instead.
201: 
202: ### Spacing utilities (for small adjustments only)
203: 
204: Use margin/padding direction utilities as **modifier wrappers** for standardized spacer amounts.
205: Form: `margin-[direction]` + `margin-[size]` (applied together on a wrapper div).
206: 
207: ⚠️ Do NOT use these for complex component-level spacing — create a custom class instead (see below).
208: 
209: **Spacing wrapper pattern (preferred for component spacing):**
210: 
211: Wrap the child element in a `<div>` and apply spacing utilities to the wrapper — not to the content element itself.
212: 
213: Use this pattern when:
214: - Element is inside a Webflow Symbol/component (instance-specific spacing)
215: - Element is a CSS Grid child where gap utility does not apply
216: - You need different spacing on one instance without affecting all others
217: 
218: ```html
219: <!-- CORRECT: wrapper owns spacing -->
220: <div class="margin-bottom margin-medium">
221:   <p class="text-size-regular">Paragraph text</p>
222: </div>
223: 
224: <!-- WRONG: margin applied to content element directly -->
225: <p class="text-size-regular margin-bottom margin-medium">Paragraph text</p>
226: ```
227: 
228: ---
229: 
230: ## Layer 3: When to Create a NEW Custom Class
231: 
232: Create a new custom class when **none of the above covers the need**. Custom classes use `_` (underscore) to separate component from element.
233: 
234: ### Naming convention
235: 
236: ```
237: [component-name]_[element-name]
238: ```
239: 
240: - `component-name`: the section or component this belongs to. Slugify, lowercase, no underscores.
241: - `element-name`: the element's role within the component. Slugify, lowercase, dashes allowed.
242: 
243: **Component wrapper = `[name]_component`; children = `[name]_[el]`; nested = `[a]_[b]_[el]`. The `_component` suffix signals this is the outermost wrapper of a reusable component.**
244: 
245: Examples:
246: | Element | New class name |
247: |---|---|
248: | Nav outermost wrapper | `nav_component` |
249: | Nav brand/logo child | `nav_brand` |
250: | Nav menu link (nested) | `nav_menu_link` |
251: | Hero section background layer | `hero_background-layer` |
252: | Nav bar link item | `navbar_link` |
253: | Pricing card wrapper | `pricing-card_component` |
254: | Pricing card CTA area | `pricing-card_cta-wrapper` |
255: | Team member photo | `team_headshot` |
256: | Footer copyright text | `footer_copyright` |
257: 
258: **Prefix strategy — global vs page-specific:**
259: - Element shared across multiple pages → generic prefix only: `card_wrapper`, `faq_item`, `nav_link`
260: - Element only on one specific page → add page slug prefix: `home_hero-text`, `about_team-grid`
261: - Never apply a page-prefixed class (`home_*`, `about_*`) to elements on other pages.
262: 
263: ### The 5 mandatory cases for NEW custom class
264: 
265: #### CASE 1 — Layout (flex/grid/positioning)
266: **CF never provides layout utility classes.** Any flex container, grid, positioning, or size constraint = custom class.
267: 
268: ```
269: ALWAYS create new:
270:   hero_content-grid       ← flex/grid layout
271:   hero_text-block         ← width/sizing within layout
272:   navbar_inner-wrapper    ← flex between logo and links
273:   feature_icon-wrapper    ← sized icon container
274: ```
275: 
276: #### CASE 2 — Unique visual treatment not covered by tokens
277: Decorative backgrounds, gradients, shadows, borders, clip-paths, custom radii NOT in the token library.
278: 
279: ```
280: ALWAYS create new:
281:   hero_gradient-bg        ← unique gradient
282:   card_shadow-layer       ← box-shadow not in library
283:   section_divider-line    ← decorative border
284: ```
285: 
286: #### CASE 3 — Recurring component elements (managed as a group)
287: When the same styled element appears 4+ times inside a component (e.g., every `li` in a feature list), create ONE custom class so all instances update together.
288: 
289: ```
290: ALWAYS create new:
291:   feature-list_item       ← used on every <li> in the feature list
292:   nav_menu-link           ← every link in the nav
293:   footer_column-heading   ← every column header in footer
294: ```
295: 
296: #### CASE 4 — Component-specific responsive overrides
297: When the element needs different spacing/layout/sizing at tablet or mobile that conflicts with the global utility value at that breakpoint.
298: 
299: ```
300: ALWAYS create new:
301:   hero_text-block         ← needs width:100% at mobile but 50% at desktop
302: ```
303: 
304: #### CASE 5 — Combo class variant
305: When a component has 2+ visual variants of the same base element, use a base custom class + `is-[variant]` combo.
306: 
307: ```
308: Base:    button
309: Combo:   button is-secondary  ← CF V2.2 shipped secondary variant
310: Combo:   button is-text       ← CF V2.2 shipped text/link variant
311: Combo:   button is-ghost      ← custom variant (not CF default — declare in new_classes)
312: ```
313: 
314: **CF V2.2 only ships `is-secondary` and `is-text` as button combos. `is-brand` and `is-outline` are NOT in CF V2.2 — any such variant must be declared as a new combo class.**
315: 
316: `is-` prefix classes are always combos — never standalone.
317: 
318: ---
319: 
320: ## Layer 4: Decision Flowchart
321: 
322: ```
323: For EACH element in the Figma design:
324: 
325: 1. Is it a STRUCTURAL wrapper (page, main, section, padding, container)?
326:    YES → Use mandatory Layer 1 class. STOP.
327: 
328: 2. Does it need a TYPOGRAPHY style change from HTML default?
329:    YES → Pick from Layer 2 typography utilities. STOP.
330:        → Need multiple utilities? Stack max 3. Beyond 3 = custom class.
331: 
332: 3. Does it need a COLOR from the project token library?
333:    YES → Use `text-color-*` / `background-color-*` / `border-color-*` from library. STOP.
334: 
335: 4. Is it a BUTTON?
336:    YES → Start with `button`. Add `is-[variant]` combo only if variant exists. STOP.
337: 
338: 5. Is it SHOW/HIDE responsive behavior only?
339:    YES → Use `hide-*` utility. STOP.
340: 
341: 6. Does it need LAYOUT (flex, grid, columns, positioning, sizing)?
342:    YES → Create NEW custom class `[component]_[element]`. Add to new_classes.
343: 
344: 7. Does it have UNIQUE VISUAL treatment (gradient, shadow, special border, custom radius)?
345:    YES → Create NEW custom class. Add to new_classes.
346: 
347: 8. Is it a RECURRING element within a component (same style, 4+ instances)?
348:    YES → Create ONE custom class shared by all instances. Add to new_classes.
349: 
350: 9. Does it need BREAKPOINT OVERRIDES that conflict with the global utility?
351:    YES → Create NEW custom class with breakpoint styles. Add to new_classes.
352: 
353: 10. Does it have COMPONENT-SPECIFIC SPACING (not standard section padding)?
354:     YES → Create NEW custom class. Add to new_classes.
355: ```
356: 
357: ---
358: 
359: ## Layer 5: Hard Rules (Never Break)
360: 
361: ### Maximum stacking
362: Never stack more than **4 classes on one element** — 4 is the absolute CF maximum.
363: 1–2 classes: ideal. 3 classes: acceptable but justify it. 4: only when no merge option exists.
364: 5+: always merge into a single custom class, no exceptions.
365: 
366: ```html
367: <!-- BAD: 6 classes = maintenance nightmare -->
368: <div class="flex-row justify-between align-center gap-2rem padding-top-4rem text-color-primary">
369: 
370: <!-- GOOD: custom class handles layout, utility handles color -->
371: <div class="hero_content-row text-color-primary">
372: ```
373: 
374: ### Layout utilities first, custom class as fallback
375: CF V2.2 ships real layout utilities. Apply in this order:
376: 1. Flex row → `flex-horizontal` + `gap-[token]`
377: 2. Flex column → `flex-vertical` + `gap-[token]`
378: 3. N-column grid → `grid-[N]-col` (+ `-tab`/`-mobile` for column reflow)
379: 4. Responsive auto grid → `grid-autofit-[size]` / `grid-autofill-[size]`
380: 5. **Only create a custom layout class** when utilities cannot express the layout
381:    (unique child sizing, >6 columns, asymmetric tracks, specific offset positioning).
382: 
383: ```html
384: <!-- CORRECT: layout utilities for simple flex/grid -->
385: <div class="flex-horizontal gap-medium">
386: 
387: <!-- CORRECT: custom class when utilities can't cover it -->
388: <div class="pricing_card-inner">   ← create this in new_classes when truly needed
389: ```
390: 
391: ### No duplicate semantics
392: Never have two classes doing the same CSS property on the same element.
393: 
394: ```html
395: <!-- WRONG: both set text color -->
396: <p class="text-color-primary hero_description">   ← hero_description also has color
397: 
398: <!-- CORRECT: one source of truth per property -->
399: <p class="text-color-primary hero_description">   ← hero_description has no color
400: ```
401: 
402: ### REM exceptions — do not blindly convert all px values
403: 
404: - **Borders:** Keep as literal `1px` — do NOT convert to rem. Retina displays handle px borders correctly; rem borders can blur. (CF border-width-thin = 1px, normal = 0.125rem, bold = 0.25rem)
405: - **Typography minimum:** 14px = `0.875rem` is acceptable for small labels/captions. Never go below 12px (0.75rem).
406: - **Tiny gaps:** 2px = `0.125rem` is OK for hairline visual gaps. Avoid irrational decimals like `8.4375rem`.
407: - **Spacing: use utility class (`margin-medium`, `gap-large`) that references a Layout variable — the variable auto-provides tablet/mobile values. Never compute px/16 for spacing. Token-snap to the nearest scale value instead.**
408: 
409: ### Color ONLY from library or token
410: Never hardcode a hex value in a custom class when that color exists as a Figma token in the per-project library. Reference the library class instead.
411: 
412: ```html
413: <!-- WRONG: redundant when text-color-primary exists -->
414: <p class="hero_description">   ← hero_description has color:#FF5733 hardcoded
415: 
416: <!-- CORRECT -->
417: <p class="text-color-primary hero_description">   ← utility handles color, custom handles layout
418: ```
419: 
420: ### Semantic HTML tags match content role
421: 
422: | Content type | Use tag |
423: |---|---|
424: | Navigation | `<nav>` |
425: | Page sections | `<section>` (must have a heading inside) |
426: | Blog post / product card / self-contained content | `<article>` |
427: | Sidebar / supplementary content | `<aside>` |
428: | Heading hierarchy | `<h1>` once per page, `<h2>`–`<h6>` nested without skipping |
429: | Inline text variation | `<span>` |
430: | Generic block | `<div>` |
431: | Generic inline | `<span>` |
432: | Self-contained content (blog post, product card) | `<article>` |
433: | Supplementary / sidebar content | `<aside>` |
434: | Image + caption pair | `<figure>` (with `<figcaption>`) |
435: | Sub-header within a section or article | `<header>` |
436: | Contact / authorship info | `<address>` |
437: | Navigation group (navbar, breadcrumbs, footer links) | `<nav>` |
438: 
439: ---
440: 
441: ## HTML Contract Output Format
442: 
443: For each section, output this structure:
444: 
445: ```html
446: <!-- section_id: hero -->
447: <section class="section_hero">
448:   <div class="padding-global">
449:     <div class="container-large">
450:       <div class="padding-section-large">
451: 
452:         <!-- Content row: CASE 1 — layout = new class -->
453:         <div class="hero_content-row">
454: 
455:           <!-- Text block: CASE 1 — sizing = new class -->
456:           <div class="hero_text-block">
457:             <!-- heading: Layer 2 utility only, no new class needed -->
458:             <h1 class="heading-style-h1 text-color-primary">Headline here</h1>
459: 
460:             <!-- body: Layer 2 utility only -->
461:             <p class="text-size-medium text-style-muted">Description here</p>
462: 
463:             <!-- button: base + combo variant -->
464:             <a class="button is-brand">CTA</a>
465:           </div>
466: 
467:           <!-- Image: CASE 2 — unique visual = new class -->
468:           <div class="hero_image-wrapper">
469:             <img class="hero_hero-image" src="" alt="">
470:           </div>
471: 
472:         </div>
473:       </div>
474:     </div>
475:   </div>
476: </section>
477: ```
478: 
479: ---
480: 
481: ## new_classes Entry Format
482: 
483: For every class you invent (all CASE 1–5 above), add ONE entry to the blueprint `new_classes` array:
484: 
485: ```json
486: {
487:   "name": "hero_content-row",
488:   "cf_category": "spacing",
489:   "webflow_property": "display",
490:   "value": "flex",
491:   "reason": "Flex row layout for hero text + image side-by-side. No CF utility covers flex layout — custom class required (Case 1)."
492: }
493: ```
494: 
495: `cf_category` pick:
496: - Layout/flex/grid/positioning → `spacing`
497: - Unique background/shadow/border → use closest: `background-color`, `border-color`, `border-radius`
498: - Component-specific text → `font-size` or `font-weight`
499: 
500: `reason` MUST reference the case number (Case 1–5) from this guide. This is auditable evidence.
501: 
502: ---
503: 
504: ## Pre-output Checklist
505: 
506: Before finalizing HTML contracts and new_classes, verify:
507: 
508: - [ ] Every section has `section_[id]` → `padding-global` → `container-*` → `padding-section-*` skeleton.
509: - [ ] No layout (flex/grid) via utility classes — all layout is custom class.
510: - [ ] No element has more than 4 classes stacked.
511: - [ ] Every color references a library class (`text-color-*`, `background-color-*`) — no hardcoded hex in custom classes.
512: - [ ] Every `new_classes` entry has a `reason` citing Case 1–5.
513: - [ ] No class in `cf_classes[]` (per section) is missing from the library OR `new_classes` list.
514: - [ ] `is-*` combo classes are always paired with a base class on the same element.
515: - [ ] `section_[id]` class name matches `section_id` in the blueprint JSON.
516: - [ ] Heading hierarchy: one `<h1>` per page, levels not skipped.
517: - [ ] No duplicate CSS property coverage from two classes on the same element.
518: 
519: ---
